body:
Considering the following code

```
struct Foo<'a> {
    foo: &'a str
}

struct Bar<'a> {
    foo: &'a mut Foo<'a>
}

fn do_stuff(foo: &mut Foo) {
//    Bar::new(foo);
    Bar { foo: foo };
}

fn do_stuff(foo: &mut Foo) {
    Bar { foo: foo };
}
```

Compiling on Rust nightly gives the following error
```
error[E0495]: cannot infer an appropriate lifetime for lifetime parameter `'a` due to conflicting requirements
  --> <anon>:11:5
   |
11 |     Bar { foo: foo };
   |     ^^^
   |
note: first, the lifetime cannot outlive the anonymous lifetime #1 defined on the body at 9:27...
  --> <anon>:9:28
   |
9  |   fn do_stuff(foo: &mut Foo) {
   |  ____________________________^ starting here...
10 | | //    Bar::new(foo);
11 | |     Bar { foo: foo };
12 | | }
   | |_^ ...ending here
note: ...so that reference does not outlive borrowed content
  --> <anon>:11:16
   |
11 |     Bar { foo: foo };
   |                ^^^
note: but, the lifetime must be valid for the anonymous lifetime #2 defined on the body at 9:27...
  --> <anon>:9:28
   |
9  |   fn do_stuff(foo: &mut Foo) {
   |  ____________________________^ starting here...
10 | | //    Bar::new(foo);
11 | |     Bar { foo: foo };
12 | | }
   | |_^ ...ending here
note: ...so that expression is assignable (expected &mut Foo<'_>, found &mut Foo<'_>)
  --> <anon>:11:16
   |
11 |     Bar { foo: foo };
   |                ^^^

error: aborting due to previous error

```
This is not really helpful because both lifetimes are starting and ending on the same lines, so I don't know why there are two distinct lifetimes here.

Compiling on stable gives this error, which is less detailed but hints at a possible fix (which effectively fix the issue)

```
error[E0495]: cannot infer an appropriate lifetime due to conflicting requirements
  --> <anon>:11:5
   |
11 |     Bar { foo: foo };
   |     ^^^
   |
help: consider using an explicit lifetime parameter as shown: fn do_stuff<'a>(foo: &'a mut Foo<'a>)
  --> <anon>:9:1
   |
9  |   fn do_stuff(foo: &mut Foo) {
   |  _^ starting here...
10 | | //    Bar::new(foo);
11 | |     Bar { foo: foo };
12 | | }
   | |_^ ...ending here

error: aborting due to previous error
```

If there is no reason for this hint to have been removed, maybe adding it back would help.
